LOCALITY: Rancho Santa Barbara (aka Lone Star Ranch, restricted access)
TRIP COMMENTS: Weather: mid 40oF at 0700, 65oF by 1100 hrs. No wind, cloudless. --Coverage: Melissa Kelly and I contributed to the annual Lake Cachuma Bald Eagle count. Ours was one of 10 or so groups ferried to various portions of the lake. We covered the east portion of lake from Santa Ynez Point S to Rancho San Fernando Rey as shown on the map. The position of the boom line is approximate. Our hike bordered a cattle pasture, but further to the SE it became an E facing oak woodland with a healthy understory of Salvia, Baccharis, Toxicodendron, Ceanothus. We observed at several points along the 1.0 mi. hike. The summary of most of the waterfowl occurred at 1030-1130 from a point immediately N of the R. San Fernando Rey HQ. We were able to look nearly a mile to the E of our S’most observations point. An Eastern Phoebe was heard and soon seen by both Melissa and myself at approx. 0930. It was singing from a bare snag 3-4m high in a live oak at the edge of the lake. See map. The spot as within 30m N of 3 large dead tree snags. Original notes mention 1 Black-bellied Plover "call heard". Because there are no other records away from the coast, this record requires more substantiation.--Other notes from Lake Cachuma: Near Santa Ynez Point, Dave Compton saw a Swamp Sparrow. On the ride back to the marina, we stopped at Sta. Cruz Bay and saw one White-faced Ibis; two individuals have been seen recently. On the return boat trip from Santa Ynez Point to the Marina we saw an approximately even distribution of Clark’s to Western Grebes, perhaps a few more Clark’s. Later, Dave Compton went out on the lake and saw ~700 grebes, nearly all of which were Western. Approx. 15 Herring Gulls were at the marina as was 1 Great-tailed Grackle. Liz Mason reports that 5 White Pelican have been seen recently on the lake.----Click on image to enlarge it.
SPECIES COMMENTS: One was perched quite close to the eagles at 0910-0950; one other was further SE of that first osprey.

TRIP COMMENTS: Yet another afternoon looking for the Bridled Tern and Red-tailed Tropicbird with Curtis Marantz (and again his notes). Highlights today were young male Greater Scaup (which had apparently been present at least a week, and likely all summer) and an Osprey. Apart from these two birds, most species seen were the same as on the previous two days. Larry Sansone and others were present. Today, Curtis scanned only from the parking lot. Clear; mild to moderate (10-15 knot) onshore breeze; mid 70s dropping to the upper 60s.

Curtis Marantz spent one last afternoon looking for the Bridled Tern and Red-tailed Tropicbird. Most of this time was spent with Michael San Miguel Jr. and me. Curtis scanned the tern colony from the parking lot and the side of the Pacific Coast Highway. He also scanned the mud flats at the far end of the boardwalk (this was several years, at least, prior to the construction of the full tidal basin). It was clear, mild (5-10 knot) onshore breeze, and mid to low 70s.

I spent the greater part of this day with others searching for the Bridled Tern and Red-tailed Tropicbird seen here yesterday. We struck out on both birds and had little to show for the day. Others present included Bruce Broadbooks, Karen Gilbert, Loren Hays, Curtis Marantz, Guy McCaskie, Joe Morlan, Larry Sansone, Doug Willick, Tom Wurster, and many others. LOCALITY: Santa Ynez River below Bradbury Dam
TRIP COMMENTS: Intent:  On the first Cachuma Christmas Bird Count on 29 December, Melissa Kelly saw a Yellow Warbler on the SYR below Bradbury Dam.  She wanted confirmation of that sighting and MAH accompanied her to this area.--Coverage and Notes:  A very birdy area.  MAH had never been here previously.  These notes do not cover the birds seen on the lake near the dam.  We birded in a light and rather cold drizzle from above the area looking NW and W from the S edge of the dam and spillway.  We crossed the riparian below the spillway twice and thus we achieved rather thorough coverage of the area.  Photos were taken by both of us of the Great Blue Heron rookery (as many as 10 nests in 2 tall Sycamore trees could have been used last breeding season judging by the newness of their construction and their completeness) and the river from the top of the spillway.  We birded a short section of far lower Hilton Creek, which was mostly dry.  Open water and tules with some cattails were present for 200m or so below the spillway.  We had an excellent overlook of this area and thus a chance to scan it for rails and moorhens—none seen or heard.  A nice stand of Red and Arroyo Willows, cottonwoods, sycamores, and very few alders dominated the rocky river bottom.  A north and west-facing hillside provided lush and moist habitat at the base of the slope.  It was dominated by live oaks, Calif. Bay, Red Willows, cottonwoods, and sycamores.  Original field notes are housed at UCSB's Cheadle Center for Biodiversity and Ecological Restoration in file: SYR at Bradbury 31 Dec 99. DOC
